  "tuneHints": {
    "goal": "Keep the piece weightless and even: a stable, slow 3/4 pulse; the LH is a soft 'breathing platform' and the RH is an unforced, singing line. Prioritize tone and balance over volume.",
    "counting": "Count 1–2–3 steadily; aim for the chord to feel like it 'arrives after 1' without rushing. Let the harmony float through beats 2–3.",
    "commonMistakes": [
      "Making the LH too loud (especially the chord) so the melody disappears",
      "Rushing the offbeat chord entry (turning it into a march)",
      "Over-pedaling so harmonies blur into each other (especially in the color-chord sections)",
      "Uneven RH quarter-notes that sound like accents rather than a calm line",
      "Letting tied tones sag in pitch/energy instead of sustaining a focused pianissimo"
    ],
    "whatToListenFor": [
      "A consistent, slow sway in 3/4 with no heavy downbeat",
      "Clear separation of harmonic changes even at pp (changes should be audible without getting louder)",
      "RH line sounds like one connected phrase, not isolated notes",
      "Tied notes remain present and luminous while LH changes underneath",
      "Color-chords (with naturals) feel like a change of light, not a wrong-note surprise"
    ]
  },
